{{Infobox Union |name= ASÍ |country= [[Iceland]] |affiliation= [[International Trade Union Confederation|ITUC]], [[ETUC]], [[TUAC]], [[Council of Nordic Trade Unions|NFS]] |members= 73,000 |full_name= Icelandic Confederation of Labour |native_name= Alþýðusamband Íslands |image= [[File:ASI logo.png|150px]] |founded= 1916 |current= |head= |dissolved_date= |dissolved_state= |merged_into= |office= [[Reykjavík]], Iceland |people= [[Drífa Snædal]], chair |website= [http://www.asi.is www.asi.is] |footnotes= }} <!-- Include all unused fields for future use. See [[template talk:Infobox Union]] for usage. -->
The '''Icelandic Confederation of Labour''' (ASÍ) (Icelandic: Alþýðusamband Íslands) is a [[trade union]] centre in [[Iceland]]. It was formed in 1916 and has a membership of 104,500, approximately half of the Icelandic workforce.
The ASÍ is affiliated with the [[International Trade Union Confederation]], the [[European Trade Union Confederation]], and the [[Council of Nordic Trade Unions]]. In October 2018 Drífa Snædal became the first female leader of the union. ==References== *{{cite book | year = 2005 | title = Trade Unions of the World | editor = [[International Centre for Trade Union Rights|ICTUR]] et al., | edition = 6th | publisher = John Harper Publishing | location = London, UK | isbn = 0-9543811-5-7 }}
==External links== * [http://www.asi.is www.asi.is] {{Is icon}} * [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073058/http://www.asi.is/ResourceImage.aspx?raid=116 Information brochure for foreign workers] {{En icon}} * [http://www.nordiclabourjournal.org/artikler/portrett/portrait-2018/article.2018-11-06.9782342756| Drífa Snædal, Iceland’s new ASÍ leader: Taking the helm in turbulent times] {{Portal|Organized labour}}
